    <p>(SOUNDBITE OF ARCHIVED RECORDING)</p>
    <p>FRANCES CARR: It's a sharing of all things in common, so it's a religious communism, living in community. We're also a celibate community, and we also believe in the confession or sin.</p>
    <p>SHARON: But Sister Frances also recognized that Shakerism (ph) was not the best fit for everyone, and not just because of celibacy. In her autobiography "Growing Up Shaker," she writes about the departure of her sister and other friends from the community. For most people, she said, putting God ahead of self and giving up independence was simply too much - not for her. She said that once she became a Shaker, she never felt alone.</p>
    <p>(SOUNDBITE OF ARCHIVED RECORDING)</p>
